The paper deals with explaining observations in Bayesian networks, which is a problem commonly studied in the field of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The method proposed in the paper involves maximizing a generalized Bayes factor, which is a statistical measure commonly used in machine learning (cs.LG) and information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the use of conditional Bayes factor to measure the relevance of variables, which is a concept that is relevant to the field of statistical inference (cs.SI). Finally, the paper presents case studies on several benchmark diagnostic Bayesian networks, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the field of data science (cs.DS).
